docs.abstract: Reporters and editors at The New York Times had a backstage view of Mr. McCain’s decades in public life. Here are their reflections.

docs.lead_paragraph: I covered three of Senator McCain’s political races — his 2008 White House race, and his 2010 and 2016 Senate re-election campaigns — and each time two Mr. McCains would show up.

headline.main: Recalling the John McCain We Knew

docs.abstract: The justices will consider whether Lee Malvo may challenge his life sentences, and they also agreed to hear cases on non-unanimous juries and the insanity defense.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide whether Lee Malvo, the younger of the two men who terrorized the Washington region with sniper shootings in the fall of 2002, may challenge his sentences of life in prison without the possibility of parole.

headline.main: Supreme Court Will Hear Case of Lee Malvo, the D.C. Sniper

docs.abstract: Thousands of Islamic State fighters are still at large in Iraq and Syria, rearming and regrouping. And the group pose threats elsewhere, in Afghanistan, West Africa and the Philippines.
docs.snippet: Thousands of Islamic State fighters are still at large in Iraq and Syria, rearming and regrouping. And the group pose threats elsewhere, in Afghanistan, West Africa and the Philippines.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The fight to expel the Islamic State from its last shard of territory in Syria may be over. But the United States and its partners still face significant battles against the terrorist group, its affiliates and other networks that are less formally aligned with it elsewhere, in Afghanistan, West Africa and the Philippines.

headline.main: Its Territory May Be Gone, but the U.S. Fight Against ISIS Is Far From Over
headline.print_headline: ISIS Territory Is Gone, But the Group Persists

docs.abstract: A senior officer who escaped punishment for the ambush that killed four American soldiers will be reprimanded. A junior officer’s reprimand is rescinded.
docs.snippet: A senior officer who escaped punishment for the ambush that killed four American soldiers will be reprimanded. A junior officer’s reprimand is rescinded.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Defense Secretary Jim Mattis was livid last month when he summoned top military officials to a video conference at the Pentagon to press them about an investigation into a 2017 ambush in Niger that killed four Americans on a Green Beret team. His anger, Pentagon officials said, came from seeing news reports that junior officers were being reprimanded for the botched Niger mission while the officers directly above them were not.

headline.main: Mattis Erupts Over Niger Inquiry and Army Revisits Who Is to Blame
headline.print_headline: An Angry Mattis Forces Military To Revisit Fault in Niger Ambush
